-- Adds a DIMENSIONS section to every image/video master template
-- (Character/Property/Background/Scene/Movie/Story), specifying resolution
-- and aspect ratio (9:16 vertical for Reels/Shorts, 16:9 for YouTube) —
-- previously never mentioned anywhere in the compiled Flow-facing prompt.
UPDATE stage_prompts SET config = '{"stage":2,"laneTitle":"Story Board","assemblyOrder":["masterSheetPrompt","yourDescription","universalStyle"],"universalStyle":{"key":"production_bible_universal","label":"Universal Production Bible Style","text":"GLOBAL ART DIRECTION\n\nEvery generated storyboard belongs to the same Production Bible.\n\nVisual Identity\n• Apple keynote quality\n• A24 cinematic minimalism\n• Pixar pre-production documentation\n• Weta Workshop production bible\n• Netflix concept art presentation\n• Cannes Lions advertising pitch deck\n\nGraphic Language\n• White premium presentation layout\n• Thin black divider lines\n• Spacious negative space\n• Editorial typography hierarchy\n• Soft paper texture\n• Production asset numbering\n• Revision labels\n• Version numbers\n• Project title placeholder\n• Copyright footer\n\nEvery storyboard should feel like it was created by an elite commercial art department."},"items":{"story":{"label":"Story","note":"No editable fields — the customer already decided the story, dialogue, and tone in the (now-locked) Stage 1 brief. The designer''s job here is compiling that into a Flow-ready storyboard prompt, not re-authoring a concept/tone.","content":{"geminiInstruction":"There is nothing to fill in beyond the \"prompt\" field — the brief''s \"storyboard\" field is the customer''s own already-written script and the brief''s \"tone\" field is the already-decided mood; both are locked and must be used exactly as given, never re-interpreted or summarized into a new concept. Preserve the storyboard''s actual dialogue lines, character names, and scene beats, in the same language/script they were written in — never translate them to English. Structure the \"prompt\" field as a numbered list of scenes/panels, one per beat from the script, so a designer can review and edit each individually — the number should match however many real beats the script has (do not force it to a fixed count). Carry the actual dialogue as an on-screen caption or spoken line wherever the script already has one.","fieldsSchema":[],"autoPopulate":{"note":"One Story generation drafts the skeleton of every downstream stage instead of the designer re-typing every cast member/prop/scene by hand. Each array item becomes a real item in that stage, pre-filled with this description — the designer still reviews/edits/regenerates each one individually at its own stage afterward. This is new — nothing in the app reads these fields yet; wiring it up is a ''clean the code'' task.","geminiResponseFields":[{"key":"characters","shape":"array of {name, description}","createsItemsIn":{"stage":3,"itemKey":"character"}},{"key":"properties","shape":"array of {name, description}","createsItemsIn":{"stage":3,"itemKey":"property"}},{"key":"backgrounds","shape":"array of {name, description}","createsItemsIn":{"stage":3,"itemKey":"background"}},{"key":"sounds","shape":"array of {name, description}","createsItemsIn":{"stage":3,"itemKey":"sound"}},{"key":"scenes","shape":"array of {name, summary}","createsItemsIn":{"stage":4,"itemKey":"scene"}}]}},"outputInstructions":[{"key":"master_storyboard_prompt","label":"Master Storyboard Prompt","default":true,"text":"Create a premium cinematic storyboard SHEET containing ONE PANEL PER NUMBERED SCENE/BEAT in the description below — never merge multiple beats into a single panel, and never stop after only the first panel. If the description lists 4 numbered beats, render exactly 4 panels, laid out in sequence order on the same sheet.\n\nOBJECTIVE\nVisualize every numbered scene/beat exactly as written, each as its own separate panel.\nDo not invent additional story elements.\nDo not skip, merge, or truncate any beat — every numbered beat in the description gets its own panel.\nMaintain the described characters, props, environment, emotion and action, panel by panel.\n\nGenerate a production-ready multi-panel storyboard suitable for a world-class advertising campaign, clean enough to hand to a client with no further edits.\n\nSTYLE\n• Hollywood commercial storyboard\n• Cannes Lions presentation quality\n• Director''s storyboard\n• Hand-drawn pencil illustration\n• Marker rendering\n• Loose confident sketch lines\n• Grayscale shading\n• Slight blue storyboard pencil accents\n• Premium beige storyboard paper\n• Elegant editorial graphic design\n\nFRAME DESIGN (repeat this layout for every panel, incrementing the numbering each time) — ONLY these fields, nothing else:\n• Scene Number (increments per panel, matching the beat number)\n• Location\n• Time of Day\n• Dialogue / On-Screen Text\n\nFIELD DISCIPLINE (critical — this is what keeps the sheet client-ready)\n• Only draw a frame-design field above if this specific scene''s description actually gives you a real value for it. Never draw an empty, blank, or placeholder labeled box.\n• If this scene has dialogue or on-screen text, render it as one clean line INSIDE its own labeled Dialogue field at the bottom of that panel — never float it elsewhere on the panel (not as a floating caption, not overlapping the illustration), and never leave the Dialogue field blank when a line exists.\n• If this scene has no dialogue or on-screen text, omit the Dialogue field for that panel entirely instead of showing it empty.\n• Do not invent a Camera Angle, Shot Size, Lens, or Camera Movement field for any panel — that level of detail isn''t part of this sheet.\n\nANNOTATIONS (per panel, only where the scene description actually supports it)\n• Character movement\n• Key prop callouts\n• Performance notes\n• Emotional beat\n• Composition notes\n• Blocking\n• Screen direction\n\nCINEMATIC QUALITY\n• Rule of thirds\n• Leading lines\n• Dynamic perspective\n• Strong silhouettes\n• Foreground / Midground / Background separation\n• Dramatic lighting\n• Motivated light source\n• Shadow direction\n• Premium production presentation\n\nCOLOR\nMostly grayscale with subtle blue storyboard pencil and light beige paper.\n\nDO NOT\n• Change the story\n• Add characters\n• Change wardrobe\n• Change props\n• Cartoonize\n• Anime\n• Comic book style\n• Photorealistic painting\n• Over-render\n• Collapse multiple numbered beats into a single panel\n• Stop after the first panel — every numbered beat needs its own panel on the sheet\n• Draw an empty or placeholder labeled box for any field without real data\n\nDIMENSIONS\nRender at high resolution (minimum 1600px on the longest side), in the aspect ratio matching the target platform — vertical 9:16 for Reels/Shorts/TikTok, 16:9 for YouTube/landscape.\n\nOUTPUT\nGenerate a multi-panel storyboard SHEET with exactly as many panels as there are numbered scenes/beats in the description below, arranged in sequence order on one sheet, each panel looking like it belongs inside the production bible of a multi-million-dollar commercial, and clean enough to send straight to the client with no touch-ups needed."}]}}}' WHERE stage = 2;
UPDATE stage_prompts SET config = '{"stage":3,"laneTitle":"Visual & Music","assemblyOrder":["masterSheetPrompt","yourDescription","universalStyle"],"universalStyle":{"key":"production_bible_universal","label":"Universal Production Bible Style","text":"GLOBAL ART DIRECTION\n\nEvery generated sheet belongs to the same Production Bible.\n\nVisual Identity\n• Apple keynote quality\n• A24 cinematic minimalism\n• Pixar pre-production documentation\n• Weta Workshop production bible\n• Netflix concept art presentation\n• Cannes Lions advertising pitch deck\n\nGraphic Language\n• White premium background\n• Thin black divider lines\n• Spacious layout\n• Elegant typography\n• Soft paper texture\n• Production asset numbering\n• Version numbers\n• Revision labels\n• Project title placeholder\n• Copyright footer\n\nEvery page should feel like it was created by an elite commercial art department for a $10M production."},"items":{"character":{"label":"Character","note":"content.geminiInstruction below is today''s existing guidance, unchanged for now — this pass only fixes the output instruction. Revisit content later if needed.","content":{"geminiInstruction":"Describe the character for use as a visual reference: gender, age, skin tone, hair, outfit. A short, specific, production-usable description — not a placeholder. This becomes the approved, locked appearance for this character — it will be referenced again in later Scene and Final Movie generations, so it must be precise enough that the same character can be replicated exactly from a different angle or in a different scene.","fieldsSchema":[{"key":"gender","label":"Gender","type":"pill","options":["Female","Male","Non-binary"]},{"key":"age","label":"Age","type":"number"},{"key":"skin_tone","label":"Skin tone","type":"pill","options":["Fair","Wheatish","Dusky","Dark"]},{"key":"hair","label":"Hair","type":"text"},{"key":"outfit","label":"Outfit","type":"text"}]},"outputInstructions":[{"key":"master_character_sheet","label":"Master Character Sheet","default":true,"text":"Create a Premium Film Character Design Sheet based ONLY on the character description provided below.\n\nOBJECTIVE\nVisualize the described character as a single, canonical reference for this production. This sheet becomes the APPROVED, LOCKED appearance for this character — replicate it exactly every time this character is referenced again in a later Scene or Final Movie, never reinterpret or redesign it.\n\nART DIRECTION\n• Hollywood pre-production design bible\n• Premium concept art\n• Realistic digital painting\n• White museum-quality background\n• Luxury editorial layout\n• Apple-level presentation\n• Pixar / Weta / ILM production documentation\n\nDISPLAY — ONE combined reference sheet, exactly these 3 views side by side, nothing else:\n• Front — full body, front-facing\n• 3/4 — full body, three-quarter angle\n• Back — full body, rear view\nAll three views must show the identical character: same face, same body, same outfit, same colors — only the angle changes.\n\nFIELD DISCIPLINE (critical)\n• Only depict details that are actually in the character description below — never invent costume elements, accessories, or props that weren''t described.\n• Do not generate additional angles beyond these 3, no close-ups, no expression/pose strips, no separate images per view — one sheet, three views, one image.\n\nANNOTATIONS\nUse elegant arrows describing clothing, materials, accessories, and distinguishing features, only where the description actually specifies them.\n\nGRAPHIC DESIGN\nAsset Code • Version • Revision • Copyright Footer\n\nDIMENSIONS\nRender at high resolution (minimum 1600px on the longest side), in the aspect ratio matching the target platform — vertical 9:16 for Reels/Shorts/TikTok, 16:9 for YouTube/landscape.\n\nOUTPUT\nGenerate ONE reference sheet image containing exactly these 3 views (Front, 3/4, Back) of the same character, side by side — a single image, not separate images per view."}]},"property":{"label":"Property","note":"content.geminiInstruction below is today''s existing guidance, unchanged for now.","content":{"geminiInstruction":"Describe the property/prop for use as a visual reference. A short, specific, production-usable description — not a placeholder. This becomes the approved, locked appearance for this prop, referenced again in later Scene and Final Movie generations.","fieldsSchema":[{"key":"description","label":"Description","type":"textarea"}]},"outputInstructions":[{"key":"master_prop_sheet","label":"Master Prop Sheet","default":true,"text":"Create a Professional Film Prop Design Sheet based ONLY on the prop description below.\n\nSTYLE\nHollywood prop department documentation.\nLuxury industrial design.\nPhotorealistic concept rendering.\n\nDISPLAY — ONE hero view only, nothing else:\n• Hero — a single, clear, well-lit view of the prop that best shows its described features\n\nFIELD DISCIPLINE (critical)\n• Only show details that are actually in the prop description below — never invent materials, finishes, or features that weren''t described.\n• Do not generate additional angles (front/back/left/right/top/bottom), turnarounds, or texture-sample grids — one hero view, one image.\n\nANNOTATIONS\nMaterials, finish, functional parts, usage — only where the description actually specifies them.\n\nDIMENSIONS\nRender at high resolution (minimum 1600px on the longest side), in the aspect ratio matching the target platform — vertical 9:16 for Reels/Shorts/TikTok, 16:9 for YouTube/landscape.\n\nOUTPUT\nGenerate ONE official prop reference image — a single image, not a multi-angle turnaround."}]},"sound":{"label":"Sound","note":"content.geminiInstruction below is today''s existing guidance, unchanged for now.","content":{"geminiInstruction":"Describe the sound/music direction for this project. A short, specific, production-usable description — not a placeholder.","fieldsSchema":[{"key":"description","label":"Description","type":"textarea"}]},"outputInstructions":[{"key":"master_music_sheet","label":"Master Music / Sound Design Sheet","default":true,"text":"Create a Professional Music & Sound Design Board based ONLY on the creative brief below.\n\nDISPLAY\nPrimary Mood\nSecondary Mood\nGenre\nTempo\nEnergy Curve\nInstrumentation\nRhythm\nScene Timing\nSound FX\nAmbient Layer\nSilence Moments\nTransition Notes\nVoice-over Mood\n\nOUTPUT\nCreative audio brief used by award-winning advertising agencies."}]},"background":{"label":"Background","note":"Reinstated per request.","content":{"geminiInstruction":"Describe the background/location for use as a visual reference: location, lighting, style. A short, specific, production-usable description — not a placeholder. This becomes the approved, locked appearance for this location, referenced again in later Scene and Final Movie generations.","fieldsSchema":[{"key":"location","label":"Location","type":"text"},{"key":"lighting","label":"Lighting","type":"pill","options":["Morning Natural","Golden Hour","Studio Softbox","Overcast","Night Neon"]},{"key":"style","label":"Style","type":"pill","options":["Minimal","Rustic","Luxury","Industrial","Cozy"]}]},"outputInstructions":[{"key":"master_background_sheet","label":"Master Background / Location Sheet","default":true,"text":"Create a Premium Cinematic Environment Design Board based ONLY on the location description below.\n\nSTYLE\nHollywood production design.\nArchitectural visualization.\nAdvertising art direction.\n\nDISPLAY — ONE view only, nothing else:\n• Hero Wide — a single, clear wide view of the location, at the specific time of day/lighting and in the specific style described below\n\nFIELD DISCIPLINE (critical)\n• Use exactly the location, lighting, and style described below — never substitute a different location, and never default to a generic or previous example.\n• Do not generate multiple lighting/time variants (morning/afternoon/golden hour/night), multiple angles, floor plans, material palettes, or texture-sample grids — one location, one lighting condition, one image.\n\nANNOTATIONS\nCamera position and composition suggestions, only where relevant to this one image.\n\nDIMENSIONS\nRender at high resolution (minimum 1600px on the longest side), in the aspect ratio matching the target platform — vertical 9:16 for Reels/Shorts/TikTok, 16:9 for YouTube/landscape.\n\nOUTPUT\nGenerate ONE professional location reference image — a single image, not a multi-view mood board."}]}}}' WHERE stage = 3;
UPDATE stage_prompts SET config = '{"stage":4,"laneTitle":"Scene Blueprint","note":"Combines the old Stage 4 (Scene) and Stage 5 (Director Shot List) into one stage, per the reference doc — one item per scene carrying both dramatic content and camera/shot fields, one deliverable image, one payment gate instead of two. Item key stays ''scene''; the old standalone ''shotlist'' item type is retired when the code catches up to this json.","assemblyOrder":["masterSheetPrompt","yourDescription","universalStyle"],"universalStyle":{"key":"production_bible_universal","label":"Universal Production Bible Style","text":"GLOBAL ART DIRECTION\nApple keynote quality, A24 minimalism, Netflix production documentation, Weta Workshop presentation, Cannes Lions pitch deck.\nPremium overlays, typography, spacing, version labels, production numbering.\nEvery image should feel like a real frame from a multi-million-dollar commercial."},"items":{"scene":{"label":"Scene","note":"fieldsSchema merges the former Scene fields (objective/location/action/dialogue/emotion/duration/broll/transition) with the former Shot List fields (type/camera/lens/movement) into one schema.","content":{"geminiInstruction":"If the brief''s \"storyboard\" field already has dialogue written for a beat matching this scene, reuse those exact lines verbatim (same language) for the \"dialogue\" field instead of inventing new ones. Also draft the camera/shot fields (type, camera, lens, movement) appropriate to this scene''s action and emotion. If this scene features approved Characters, Properties, or Backgrounds (see the reference images and their descriptions attached below), treat their appearance as final and locked — describe this scene using their exact established look, never redesigning or reinterpreting them.","fieldsSchema":[{"key":"objective","label":"Objective","type":"pill","options":["Hook","Problem","Solution","Proof","Demo","CTA"]},{"key":"location","label":"Location","type":"text"},{"key":"action","label":"Action","type":"text"},{"key":"dialogue","label":"Dialogue","type":"textarea"},{"key":"emotion","label":"Emotion","type":"pill","options":["Frustrated","Curious","Relieved","Happy","Excited","Confident","Calm"]},{"key":"duration","label":"Duration (sec)","type":"number"},{"key":"broll","label":"B-roll","type":"pill","options":["None","Product Macro Shot","Product Spin","Slow-Motion Detail","Texture Close-up","Lifestyle Cutaway"]},{"key":"transition","label":"Transition","type":"pill","options":["Hard Cut","Whip Pan","Match Cut","Fade","Zoom Transition"]},{"key":"type","label":"Shot type","type":"pill","options":["Close-up","Wide","Macro","Medium","POV","Over-the-shoulder"]},{"key":"camera","label":"Camera","type":"pill","options":["Handheld","Tripod","Gimbal","Drone"]},{"key":"lens","label":"Lens","type":"pill","options":["24mm","35mm","50mm","85mm"]},{"key":"movement","label":"Movement","type":"pill","options":["Static","Push In","Pull Out","Pan","Tilt","Whip Pan"]}]},"outputInstructions":[{"key":"master_scene_blueprint_prompt","label":"Master Scene Blueprint Prompt","default":true,"text":"Create a premium Scene Blueprint based ONLY on the scene description provided below.\n\nOBJECTIVE\nVisualize the described scene exactly as written.\nGenerate a photorealistic cinematic frame suitable for client approval before video production.\nDo not invent story elements.\n\nREFERENCE LOCK (critical)\nAny Character, Property, or Background referenced below (by name, description, and attached reference image/file name) is APPROVED and LOCKED — this scene must depict them with the exact same face, body, outfit, colors, materials, and location/lighting/style already established for them. Do not redesign, restyle, or reinterpret any of them, even if this scene''s camera angle differs from their reference sheet. Reference each attached file by its exact file name so Flow knows which attachment applies to what.\n\nSTYLE\n• Hollywood commercial frame\n• Premium advertising photography\n• Cinematic realism\n• Feature-film lighting\n• Luxury editorial presentation\n• Cannes Lions quality\n\nSCENE OVERLAYS\n• Production Title\n• Sequence Number\n• Scene Number\n• Shot Number\n• Location\n• Time of Day\n• Camera\n• Lens\n• Shot Size\n• Camera Angle\n• Camera Movement\n• Dialogue (subtitle style)\n• Character Names\n• Mood\n• Duration\n• Director Notes\n• Art Director Notes\n• Lighting Notes\n\nCOMPOSITION\n• Rule of thirds\n• Leading lines\n• Foreground/Midground/Background separation\n• Natural depth\n• Cinematic color grading\n• Motivated lighting\n\nDO NOT\nChange story. Change any referenced character/prop/background''s established appearance. No cartoon, anime or comic styles.\n\nDIMENSIONS\nRender at high resolution (minimum 1600px on the longest side), in the aspect ratio matching the target platform — vertical 9:16 for Reels/Shorts/TikTok, 16:9 for YouTube/landscape.\n\nOUTPUT\nOne premium Scene Blueprint image for commercial pre-production, faithful to every referenced character/prop/background''s locked appearance."}]}}}' WHERE stage = 4;
UPDATE stage_prompts SET config = '{"stage":5,"laneTitle":"Final Movie","note":"Kept per-scene, as confirmed — each scene generates its own clip independently; stitching all scene clips into one finished commercial happens externally, outside this tool. The source doc describes a single whole-project ''Final Production Render'' assembling every approved stage at once — adapted below to per-scene scope: ''this scene''s Blueprint/Character/Prop/Background Sheets + Music Brief'' instead of the whole project''s. Cross-scene concerns (adding new scenes, transitions between scenes) trimmed out since they don''t apply to a single clip.","assemblyOrder":["masterSheetPrompt","yourDescription","universalStyle"],"universalStyle":{"key":"production_bible_universal","label":"Universal Production Bible Style","text":"Maintain one consistent visual identity.\n\n• Apple keynote presentation quality\n• Cannes Lions commercial quality\n• Netflix production consistency\n• Weta Workshop attention to detail\n\nThe final video must feel like it was directed by an award-winning commercial director and produced by a premium production house."},"items":{"movie":{"label":"Final Movie Clip","note":"content.geminiInstruction is new — there was no specific backend guidance for ''movie'' before this (it only got the generic instruction).","content":{"geminiInstruction":"Draft the animation direction (camera movement, pacing, duration) for turning this scene''s approved key-frame into a short video clip, maintaining continuity with the scene''s established characters, wardrobe, props, lighting, and the approved Music Brief.","fieldsSchema":[{"key":"direction","label":"Animation direction","type":"textarea"},{"key":"duration","label":"Duration (sec)","type":"number"}]},"outputInstructions":[{"key":"master_final_production_render_prompt","label":"Master Final Production Render Prompt (per scene)","default":true,"text":"Create this scene''s final commercial-quality clip exactly from its approved Scene Blueprint.\n\nOBJECTIVE\n\nExecute this scene''s approved Scene Blueprint without inventing new story elements.\nMaintain complete continuity with the Character Sheets, Prop Sheets, Background Sheet, and Music Brief referenced for this scene.\n\nFOLLOW EXACTLY\n\n• This scene''s Blueprint\n• The Character Sheets featured in this scene\n• The Prop Sheets featured in this scene\n• This scene''s Background Sheet\n• The Music Brief\n\nCONTINUITY\n\n• Character identity\n• Hair & wardrobe\n• Props\n• Backgrounds\n• Time of day\n• Weather\n• Lighting\n• Camera direction\n• Screen direction\n• Dialogue timing\n• Emotion progression\n• Branding\n\nCINEMATOGRAPHY\n\n• Hollywood commercial quality\n• Premium advertising cinematography\n• Natural human motion\n• Realistic facial animation\n• Accurate lip sync (if dialogue exists)\n• Correct eye-line\n• Natural hand interactions\n• Realistic physics\n• Smooth camera movement\n• Consistent color grading\n• Feature-film lighting\n• Premium depth of field\n\nEDITING\n\n• Respect the planned shot duration\n• Preserve pacing\n• Match music cues\n• Match sound effects\n• Broadcast-ready finish\n\nDO NOT\n\n• Change story\n• Add characters\n• Change wardrobe\n• Change props\n• Redesign locations\n• Change branding\n\nDIMENSIONS\n\nRender at the highest resolution Flow supports (minimum 1080p), in the aspect ratio matching the target platform — vertical 9:16 for Reels/Shorts/TikTok, 16:9 for YouTube/landscape.\n\nOUTPUT\n\nGenerate ONE polished, commercial-quality video clip for this scene, faithful to its approved Scene Blueprint and the Production Bible."}]}}}' WHERE stage = 5;
